\begin_layout Subsection
Additional two-class classification metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classification accuracy is the most basic yet popular metric for evaluating
 a classifier's performance.
 However in certain scenarios using the accuracy metric alone would paint
 an incomplete picture.
 For example when one class greatly outnumbers the other, an accuracy value
 close to 1 can be misleading: if one class makes up 95% percent of all
 data points, a naive classifier that blindly assigns the label of the majority
 class to every data point will still achieve an accuracy of 95%.
 Additionally using accuracy alone is not appropriate in situations where
 misclassification errors are not considered equally important or consequential
 across the two classes.
 For instance, in the medical domain the consequences of incorrectly classfying
 healthy patients as afflicted are vastly different from those of failure
 to diagnose afflicted patients by misclassifying them as healthy.
 Therefore we need more comprehensive performance metrics that can capture
 possible imbalance between the number of data points in each class, and
 can distinguish between different types of classification errors.
 Such metrics can be defined, as shown in Figure 
