\begin_layout Standard
A confusion matrix is a simple lookup table where classification results
 are broken down by actual (across rows) and predicted (across columns)
 class membership.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the number of data points whose actual label, +1, is identical to the
 label assigned to them by the trained classifier.
 The other diagonal entry 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is similarly defined as the number of data points whose predicted class,
 -1, is equal to their actual class.
 Ideally, we want these numbers to be maximally large and the off-diagonal
 entries 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to be zero as they represent the two types of classification errors wherein
 the actual and predicted labels do not match.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the confusion matrix at hand, in addition to accuracy calculated as
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{accuracy}=\frac{A+D}{A+B+C+D},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we can define additional metrics that can mitigate the above mentioned shortcomi
ngs of accuracy, including
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{precision }=\frac{A}{A+B},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{specificity}=\frac{D}{B+D},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{recall (or sensitivity)}=\frac{A}{A+C}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These metrics provide a more complete picture of the classification results
 by separating out the two types of classification errors (accounted for
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

) that are mixed up together in the definition of accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Precision and recall are sometimes combined into a single metric, commonly
 referred to as the 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 score, defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\beta}=\left(1+\beta^{2}\right)\frac{\textrm{precision}\times\textrm{recall}}{\left(\beta^{2}\times\textrm{precision}\right)+\textrm{recall}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, if set high, gives recall more influence than precision in the weighted
 average and vice versa.
 Like accuracy, all of these additional metrics also range from 0 to 1 with
 larger values indicating a more favorable result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Additional multiclass classification metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can generalize the idea of a confusion matrix, introduced in Section
 BLAH for two-class classification problems, to form such matrices for problems
 with arbitrary number of classes.
 In general the confusion matrix associated to a classification problem
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $C\geq2$
\end_inset

 classes will be of size 
\begin_inset Formula $C\times C$
\end_inset

, whose 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i,j\right)^{\textrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 entry is the number of data points that have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}=j$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:confusion_matrix_multiclass"

\end_inset

 shows the confusion matrix computed for the four-class classifier previously
 shown in Figure BLAH.
 
